          <p>If you searched "pannus stomach" and landed here: you're in exactly the right place. <strong class="text-on-surface">Pannus stomach is the medical term for apron belly.</strong> Same condition, same tissue, same treatments — just two names for the same hanging fold of skin and fat below the lower abdomen.</p>
          <p>The word <em>pannus</em> comes from Latin, meaning "cloth" or "fold." In clinical settings, doctors use <em>pannus</em> or <em>panniculus</em> to describe the tissue. Surgeons classify it by how far it hangs: Grade 1 (covers the pubic hairline) up to Grade 5 (extends past the knees in severe cases). Most people searching for answers are Grade 1–3.</p>
          <p>Most people who live with it call it apron belly. Most doctors who treat it say pannus. Both names point to the same mechanical reality: skin that stretched beyond its elastic limit and didn't fully return.</p>
          <p>Everything on this site applies equally to both. Start with the <a href="/non-surgical-solutions/" class="text-sage-green hover:underline font-medium">Non-Surgical Guide</a> — it covers the full picture.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
